1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION
In these regulations and in the Space Allocation Agreement, the following words shall have the meaning respectively assigned to them hereunder, unless the context requires or admits otherwise:
“Agreement“ shall mean the Space Allocation Agreement and these regulations and Exhibition Manual;
Applicable Laws, shall mean the local laws and regulations of the Emirates of Dubai and the federal laws of the United Arab Emirates;
“Center User” Shall mean all the exhibitors at all the Center, Tenants of allocated space, and includes each of their agents, contractor, employees, invitees and attendees of the Exhibition;
“Exhibition” Shall mean the event as named and dated in the Space Allocation Agreement:
“Exhibitor” Shall mean any person, firm, company, association, organization and its employees, servants or agents to whom exhibit space has been allocated for the purpose of exhibiting at the Exhibition: represented by the authorized signatory of this Agreement:
“Contracted Term” Shall the contracted period under the Agreement as specifically mentioned in the Space Allocation Agreement:
“Exhibitor Manual“ shall mean the manual of the Organizer’s internal guidelines established from time to time and distributed to the Exhibitor prior to the Exhibition for the sale and orderly conduct and close of the Exhibition;
“Exhibition Material” shall mean such good, exhibits, materials equipment, stand/s, supplies, merchandise, models, exhibit items, or other property for the sole use of the Exhibition;
“Force Majeure” shall mean any event or circumstances (or a combination of events or circumstances) which are beyond the reasonable control of the relevant, party, resulting in or causing the failure by that party, resulting in or causing the ailure by that party to perform any of its obligation under this Agreement (whether in whole or in part), including without limitation. (1) revolution, riots, insurrection or other civil commotion act to terrorism or sabotage or war; (2) nuclear explosion, radioactive, biological or chemical contaminations or adiation; (3) general strikes, work stoppages, working to rule, go slow actions and or lockout; (4) any effect of the natural elements including lightening, fire, earthquakes, flood, storm, hurricane, tsunami, cyclone or tornado. Materials change in sea level or coastal subsidence; (5) explosion (other than nuclear explosion or any explosion resulting from an act or war; (6) inability to obtain necessary plant, equipment or materials due to blockade,

